108: New Year's Day (Nyårsdagen) January 1. This is a public holiday in Sweden, marking the start of the new calendar year. It is a day for rest and often for recovering from New Year's Eve celebrations.
Twelfth Night (Trettondagsafton) January 5. While not a public holiday, many businesses close early on this day. It is the eve of Epiphany and marks the end of the Christmas season for many.
Epiphany (Trettondedag jul) January 6. This is a public holiday in Sweden, commemorating the visit of the Magi to the Christ Child. It is often a quiet day for reflection.

Good Friday (Långfredagen) This is a public holiday, a movable feast day occurring on the Friday before Easter Sunday. It commemorates the crucifixion of Jesus Christ and is traditionally a solemn day.

Easter Sunday (Påskdagen) This is a public holiday, a movable feast day occurring on the first Sunday after the first full moon on or after the vernal equinox. It celebrates the resurrection of Jesus Christ and is often marked by family gatherings and Easter eggs.
Easter Monday (Annandag påsk) This is a public holiday, a movable feast day occurring on the Monday after Easter Sunday. It is another day for relaxation and family time following Easter Sunday.

Walpurgis Night (Valborgsmässoafton) April 30. This is an unofficial but widely celebrated observance. Swedes gather around bonfires, sing traditional songs, and welcome spring. It is not a day off work.
Labour Day / May Day (Första maj) May 1. This is a public holiday in Sweden, observed as International Workers' Day. It is often marked by political demonstrations and parades.

Ascension Day (Kristi himmelsfärdsdag) This is a public holiday, a movable feast day occurring 39 days after Easter Sunday, always on a Thursday. It commemorates the ascension of Jesus Christ into heaven.
Mother's Day (Mors dag) Last Sunday in May. This is an unofficial observance where mothers are celebrated. It is not a public holiday.

National Day of Sweden (Sveriges nationaldag) June 6. This is a public holiday, celebrating the election of Gustav Vasa as king in 1523 and the adoption of a new constitution in 1809. It is marked by flag-raising ceremonies and public celebrations.

Midsummer's Eve (Midsommarafton) This is an unofficial but widely observed holiday, occurring on the Friday between June 19 and June 25. Many businesses close early or are completely closed. It is one of the most important celebrations in Sweden, marked by dancing around a maypole, flower wreaths, and traditional food.
Midsummer's Day (Midsommardagen) This is a public holiday, occurring on the Saturday after Midsummer's Eve. It is a day for relaxation after the previous day's festivities.

Crayfish Party Season (Kräftskivesäsong) This is an unofficial observance, typically taking place in August. Swedes gather for outdoor parties to eat crayfish, often with schnapps and singing. It is not a specific holiday but a cultural season.

Surströmming Premiere (Surströmmingspremiären) Third Thursday in August. This is an unofficial observance marking the release of the year's fermented herring. It is a niche but significant cultural event for some.
Cinnamon Bun Day (Kanelbullens dag) October 4. This is an unofficial observance dedicated to the popular Swedish pastry, the cinnamon bun. Bakeries and cafes often offer special deals.

All Saints' Day (Alla helgons dag) This is a public holiday, a movable feast day occurring on the first Saturday in November, between November 3 and November 9. It is a day to remember deceased loved ones, often by visiting graves and lighting candles.
Father's Day (Fars dag) Second Sunday in November. This is an unofficial observance where fathers are celebrated. It is not a public holiday.

Lucia (Luciadagen) December 13. This is an unofficial but very important cultural observance, especially in schools, churches, and workplaces. It involves processions with singing, candles, and traditional saffron buns (lussekatter). It is not a public holiday.

Christmas Eve (Julafton) December 24. This is an unofficial but widely observed holiday. Most Swedes celebrate Christmas on this day, with family gatherings, gift-giving, and a traditional "julbord" (Christmas buffet). Many businesses close early or are completely closed.
Christmas Day (Juldagen) December 25. This is a public holiday in Sweden, a quieter day for family and relaxation after the Christmas Eve celebrations.
Boxing Day / Saint Stephen's Day (Annandag jul) December 26. This is a public holiday in Sweden, often used for visiting relatives or engaging in post-Christmas sales.

New Year's Eve (Nyårsafton) December 31. This is an unofficial but widely observed holiday. Many businesses close early. It is celebrated with parties, fireworks, and often a traditional dinner to welcome the new year.
